# Brainstorm / Claude scratch
.superpowers/

# Claude Code project-scoped automation IS committed (hooks, settings.json,
# skills/, agents/) so every contributor gets the same guardrails by default
# — see docs/superpowers/specs/2026-05-17-claude-automation-toolkit-design.md.
# Only the personal per-session prefs file is gitignored.
.claude/settings.local.json

# Android / Gradle build outputs
*.iml
.gradle/
.idea/
build/
local.properties
captures/
.externalNativeBuild/
.cxx/

# gradle.lockfile is tracked at app/gradle.lockfile per Gradle's
# "lockfiles should be checked in to source control" guidance.
# This entry only prevents accidental tracking of NEW module-level
# lockfiles created by `--write-locks` in modules other than `:app`.
# Today the only other module is `:detekt-rules`, which doesn't invoke
# `--write-locks` — so this entry is a forward-looking guard. See
# docs/release/SHIPPING.md §"Release-tag dependency-lock procedure" and
# CLAUDE.md "Things that have bitten" lesson on lockfile tracking.
# (The Security CI workflow still regenerates fresh each run before
# OSV-Scanner — that's independent of how the file is tracked.)
gradle.lockfile

# Settings-level lockfile is a side-effect of `--write-locks` on Gradle 9.x —
# written for every configuration in the build tree even when empty. Ours
# contains only `empty=incomingCatalogForLibs0` (the version-catalog
# resolution has nothing to lock). No audit value, regenerated on every lock
# run; ignore alongside the runtime lockfile.
settings-gradle.lockfile

# Kotlin / IntelliJ
out/
.kotlin/

# OS junk
.DS_Store
Thumbs.db

# Per-session handover scratch file — written at the end of a work session
# (see the `wrap` skill). Untracked by design; ignored here to harden against
# an accidental `git add`.
HANDOVER.md
